<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE: LANGUAGE VIEWPOINT</font><br>
<tt>Tue Mar  4 12:18:26 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I think that words are tools we use to express ourselves.  People have different abilities with regard to expressing themselves with words.  This site is a special place where people especially Vietnam Vets may unashamedly express themselves.  It's fairly obvious that men and women who have suffered the ravages of war have important experiential insights into the condition of man in general.  I have difficulty realizing how a responsible educator would be so concerned about the appearance rather than the substance.  In this life we have to live, laugh, cry, survive and suffer together.  That's what we want to protect ourselves from isn't it?  The suffering part.  Sorry, it don't work.  Hell makes Heaven more real for us.  We must share in the suffering so that we can share in the joy.  War is worse than any four letter word.  But those words tell our kids &quot;don't go there&quot;.  And that's what we really want to tell them.  You have a right to your opinion, but something in your attitude &quot;called me out&quot; and I felt obliged to respond.  Really, we need more people who are concerned for children in this &quot;now&quot; world.
<p><code>-- PBey280087@aol.com  (Corbin Bey) </code><p>


